{
  "answer": "**In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Shama aur Shair\" (The Candle and the Poet) from *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, the candle does not speak to the poet.**[^1]\n\nInstead, the poem is a monologue in which the poet addresses the candle in his \"desolate dwelling,\" envying its allure for moths while lamenting his own isolation:\n\n> Last night, I said to the candle of my desolate dwelling:  \n> \"Your tresses are combed by the wing of a moth.  \n> \n> In this world, I am like the lamp of a desert tulip,  \n> Destined for no gathering, fated for no private chamber.  \n> \n> For ages, like you, I too have burned with every breath,  \n> Yet around my flame, no moth has ever stirred its wings.  \n> \n> A hundred splendors throb within my weary soul,  \n> But from this gathering, no impassioned soul takes flight.  \n> \n> From where did you gather this world-illuminating fire,  \n> To teach a humble worm the fire that Moses knew?\"[^2]\n\nThe candle remains silent throughout the short verse, serving as a symbol for the poet's unappreciated inner fire.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Shama aur Shair\" [chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/19-shama-aur-shair/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Shama aur Shair\" [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/19-shama-aur-shair/translation/#p-8f74a7).",
